matter.

00:02:19.890 --> 00:02:23.790
So let me, let me just ask the room here.
How-How many of you guys consider yourselves

00:02:23.790 --> 00:02:25.060
gamers-in the room?

00:02:25.060 --> 00:02:26.330
[PAUSE LOOKS AROUND]

00:02:26.330 --> 00:02:29.900
Wow! That's about half. Interesting. So this
is-there'll be some internecine arguments

00:02:29.900 --> 00:02:35.260
and bloodshed at the end of this session,
I hope, while we all debate whether or not

00:02:35.260 --> 00:02:36.460
they do, in fact, matter.

00:02:36.460 --> 00:02:45.840
So, the first videogame is genuinely regarded
as a thing called "Tennis for Two", which

00:02:45.840 --> 00:02:52.349
was invented in the late 1950's by [PAUSE]
an engineer, the guy who actually invented

00:02:52.349 --> 00:02:59.060
the timers that were used on the atomic bombs
in Hiroshima and Nagasaki during World War

00:02:59.060 --> 00:03:00.060
II.

00:03:00.060 --> 00:03:04.640
He-He later became an-an engineer and so there
was some open house, I think at MIT that they

00:03:04.640 --> 00:03:14.340
were having; and this guy ginned up this very
simple device ta, it was basically, it was

00:03:14.340 --> 00:03:21.130
like a proto-palm that this guy invented.
And what's funny about that is, you know,

00:03:21.130 --> 00:03:28.030
15 years later, whatever it was when palm
finally, went- when palm dropped nationally,

00:03:28.030 --> 00:03:33.269
it was still basically the same thing.

00:03:33.269 --> 00:03:36.800
And so, it's these two things shooting a ball
at each other, it's repetitive, it's kind

00:03:36.800 --> 00:03:39.300
of like a digital approximation of an-an athletic
activity. It's repetitive, it's competitive,

00:03:39.300 --> 00:03:42.780
and it had to do with like the same thing
over and over again until someone failed and

00:03:42.780 --> 00:03:48.159
someone won. So that's how games sort of begin.
They begin in this sort of digital approximation

00:03:48.159 --> 00:03:49.700
of something that happens over and over and
over again.

00:03:49.700 --> 00:03:54.049
And then the next wave of like popular games,
you know, you get in the late 1970s, late

00:03:54.049 --> 00:04:02.470
1980s, you start seeing games like Donkey
Kong and Pacman. And suddenly, these are goal-oriented

00:04:02.470 --> 00:04:06.220
activities with a very vague storytelling
overlay.

00:04:06.220 --> 00:04:12.269
Like, for instance, Pacman has cut scenes,
which are interstitial things that go on between

00:04:12.269 --> 00:04:15.480
bits of game play. And so, you realize that
there's history between Pacman and the ghosts.

00:04:15.480 --> 00:04:22.690
There-there's something between them. And
they've obviously shared -- there's some bad

00:04:22.690 --> 00:04:23.690
blood there.

00:04:23.690 --> 00:04:30.100
And, it's not storytelling the way we have
traditionally come to understand it; but it's

00:04:30.100 --> 00:04:34.520
definitely there's something more to the game
than just the activity of going through these-these-these-these

00:04:34.520 --> 00:04:38.340
passageways. That the game designer actually
wants you to feel that there is something

00:04:38.340 --> 00:04:40.040
narratively going on here.

00:04:40.040 --> 00:04:45.710
And Donkey Kong is the same way. We don't
really know why Donkey Kong has captured Mario's

00:04:45.710 --> 00:04:50.729
girlfriend; but he has and he has to get her
back. And so, there's this-s, why did she

00:04:50.729 --> 00:04:57.150
fall into his grasp? Why does she maybe not
seem like she's fighting it quite as strong

00:04:57.150 --> 00:04:59.050
as she could be? Does she, does she actually
like Donkey Kong? These are all things you

00:04:59.050 --> 00:05:06.981
can think about within the parameters of the
Donkey Kong story. This kind of vague thing

00:05:06.981 --> 00:05:08.350
that happens in the game.

00:05:08.350 --> 00:05:14.270
So then after that, a lot of the big, commercial
games-s-s-s, the-the-the-the pendulum sorta

00:05:14.270 --> 00:05:20.780
swung the other way. They were no longer goal-oriented
activities with the vague storytelling overlay.

00:05:20.780 --> 00:05:27.400
They were actually a storytelling medium that
were organized around successfully obtaining

00:05:27.400 --> 00:05:33.761
goals. And so these, this is where the games
that I'm kind of interested in come into this

00:05:33.761 --> 00:05:36.300
and why I think games matter.

00:05:36.300 --> 00:05:41.690
And this form of storytelling that the games
started doing in the early 90s, late 80s,

00:05:41.690 --> 00:05:46.710
wherever you wanna date it from, wasn't really
very good for a long time for all sorts of

00:05:46.710 --> 00:05:47.710
technical reasons that we can talk about later.

00:05:47.710 --> 00:05:53.120
But, I think we can concede that the knock
on games for a long time was the stories weren't

00:05:53.120 --> 00:05:58.970
as good as stories in traditional medium because
well as a game the story was supposed to be

00:05:58.970 --> 00:06:03.600
stupid. It didn't matter. In a way it didn't.
What did matter if the game was fun?

00:06:03.600 --> 00:06:10.870
Well, by 2005-2006, I started to notice the
game's storytelling was actually getting pretty

00:06:10.870 --> 00:06:16.169
good, and more and more designers seemed less
satisfied with the-it's a videogame, it's

00:06:16.169 --> 00:06:20.470
supposed to be stupid-approach to game design.

00:06:20.470 --> 00:06:28.250
And so, why I think games are important is
that however garish and clumsy and sometimes

00:06:28.250 --> 00:06:33.300
ridiculous they seem, that I do think that
they constitute an entirely new form of storytelling,

00:06:33.300 --> 00:06:39.150
and moreover a really important one because
the rules of this form of storytelling are

00:06:39.150 --> 00:06:44.080
not really very well established yet. For
instance-do you have a silent protagonist

00:06:44.080 --> 00:06:47.980
or a speaking protagonist? Do you use cut
scenes? Or not use cut scenes? What is environmental

00:06:47.980 --> 00:06:54.810
storytelling and how can games use that to
their advantage? How useful is exposition

00:06:54.810 --> 00:06:55.910
in a game?

00:06:55.910 --> 00:07:01.460
There's all very-within game design circles
these are all semi-heated topics that people

00:07:01.460 --> 00:07:06.259
are making games endorsing various design
principles, and you see these things worked

00:07:06.259 --> 00:07:11.900
out now. Just about every year, a couple of
videogames come out the really reset the table

00:07:11.900 --> 00:07:14.650
when it comes to what we can expect from videogames'
storytelling. And there is not another medium

00:07:14.650 --> 00:07:23.210
that I know of that is so open to sudden,
swift decisive game-changing sort of developments;

00:07:23.210 --> 00:07:26.220
and that's what I find really exciting about
it.

00:07:26.220 --> 00:07:33.480
And this is why I focus in this book on narrative
games; it's why I talk about narrative games.

00:07:33.480 --> 00:07:42.259
Partially because I'm a writer myself, I'm
a fiction writer so storytelling is my fascination.

00:07:42.259 --> 00:07:45.590
It's my passion. It's what I'm most interested
in.

00:07:45.590 --> 00:07:47.560
So there's a lot of hard-core game people,
a lot of people who seriously love their games

00:07:47.560 --> 00:07:49.770
who kind of don't like narrative games and
think the narrative game is kind of a dead

00:07:49.770 --> 00:07:51.690
end. And they're more interested in the mechanics
of play and how you tell stories just through

00:07:51.690 --> 00:07:56.310
play without all those bothersome, clunky,
storytelling crap that games have never done

00:07:56.310 --> 00:07:59.840
very well to begin with. And I have sympathy
for that position.

00:07:59.840 --> 00:08:05.319
But I ultimately, for me, I-I kind of reject
it because I think that there is a reason

00:08:05.319 --> 00:08:11.200
why that the game medium desperately wants
to become a storytelling medium and I think

00:08:11.200 --> 00:08:14.410
it does. You can see it. I think it desperately
wants to become a storytelling medium because

00:08:14.410 --> 00:08:16.910
human beings desperately love to be told stories.

00:08:16.910 --> 00:08:23.380
And so my passion and my argument is that
I don't want game narratives to be unnecessarily

00:08:23.380 --> 00:08:32.400
stupid, anymore. And-and that's kind of why
I wrote this book, and I wanna distinguish

00:08:32.400 --> 00:08:39.520
between unnecessarily stupid things in games
and things that are kind of core to the game

00:08:39.520 --> 00:08:40.520
experience.

00:08:40.520 --> 00:08:44.570
My girlfriend is an actor and I just came
back from Texas seeing her perform in a couple

00:08:44.570 --> 00:08:48.430
uh Shakespearean performances. One of which
was Much Ado About Nothing and the other which

00:08:48.430 --> 00:08:50.860
was Hamlet. And I realized watching these
performances that there are all of these core

00:08:50.860 --> 00:08:54.029
artificialities to the stage.

00:08:54.029 --> 00:08:57.360
Like the Shakespearean soliloquy's about as
ridiculous as a convention as you could possibly

00:08:57.360 --> 00:09:00.630
think. When one character turns to the audience
and speaks his heart while people are standing

00:09:00.630 --> 00:09:04.180
two feet away from him, and we're supposed
that this is-that this is not obviously a

00:09:04.180 --> 00:09:10.220
realistic depiction of what is supposed to
be going on in the play world. It's a stylized

00:09:10.220 --> 00:09:16.430
approximation of something that's going on
in the character's head.

00:09:16.430 --> 00:09:17.520
So games obviously have this kind of stuff
happening all the time. And novels happen

00:09:17.520 --> 00:09:23.380
in chapters, which is also a very weird, artificially,
arbitrary kind of convention to the form that

00:09:23.380 --> 00:09:25.460
we don't really question.

00:09:25.460 --> 00:09:32.959
So- what I think games need to be doing more
of is learning how to soften these things

00:09:32.959 --> 00:09:37.580
that seem ridiculous into things that seem
acceptably ridiculous within the medium; and

00:09:37.580 --> 00:09:41.350
separating those from the things that are
unnecessarily ridiculous and just coming up

00:09:41.350 --> 00:09:47.630
with some very stronger ground rules as to
how the medium works best.

00:09:47.630 --> 00:09:54.270
And I'm sure all of you have heard the "Are
games art?" question, and I'm not going to

00:09:54.270 --> 00:10:01.630
address that much beyond to say, it's the
wrong question. It's not the question is not,

00:10:01.630 --> 00:10:05.620
"Are games art?" but the question is, "Can
artists express themselves through this medium?"

00:10:05.620 --> 00:10:09.220
And I think the answer to that question is,
"Absolutely, yes!"

00:10:09.220 --> 00:10:14.400
And a lot of the basis of people saying games
are not art comes down to this weird misunderstanding

00:10:14.400 --> 00:10:19.540
that because games are quote "games" and because
they have goals, that like chess, or like

00:10:19.540 --> 00:10:20.630
football, or like basketball they can't really
be art.

00:10:20.630 --> 00:10:24.170
Roger Ebert's position is that Michael Jordan's
not an artist. And that is true, but Michael

00:10:24.170 --> 00:10:28.540
Jordan is also not telling a story.

00:10:28.540 --> 00:10:37.350
And I think any medium that is- serves as
a storytelling medium provides a basis for

00:10:37.350 --> 00:10:38.470
an artistic experience.

00:10:38.470 --> 00:10:49.130
'Cause to me an artistic experience-whether
it's like a good artistic experience or a

00:10:49.130 --> 00:10:58.180
bad artistic experience or a high or a low
art artistic experience-to me an artistic

00:10:58.180 --> 00:11:05.130
experiences allows you to go into something
created by another person or another group

00:11:05.130 --> 00:11:32.110
of people and come out of it transformed somehow-emotionally.
And some games have done that to me. And I'm

00:11:32.110 --> 00:11:40.470
sure that some games have done that to those
of you who game. Maybe not as many as we'd

00:11:40.470 --> 00:11:41.470
like but it-it's definitely happened.

00:11:41.470 --> 00:11:50.890
And so I think the biggest problem with this
question for a lot of people who are ignorant

00:11:50.890 --> 00:12:02.829
of the medium is that just-just-just this
term game gets in the way, videogame. It just

00:12:02.829 --> 00:12:03.829
sounds so ridiculous.

00:12:03.829 --> 00:12:07.990
And I think that everyone agrees that it's
the worst title for something ever. But I

00:12:07.990 --> 00:12:15.470
think we're kind of stuck with it; but I would
also remind you that thinking about "movie"

00:12:15.470 --> 00:12:30.170
for a minute it's a -- [CHUCKLES] -- it's
a pretty dumb name for that medium as well.

00:12:30.170 --> 00:12:44.730
Something-a movie is something that moves.
And it's better than talkie though, I suppose.

00:12:44.730 --> 00:12:54.399
So I would hope that at some point this idea
of things being games or game-like -- that

00:12:54.399 --> 00:13:01.520
all the childish, adolescent associations
we have with the idea of games will-will sort

00:13:01.520 --> 00:13:02.540
of fade.

00:13:02.540 --> 00:13:12.250
And I think it is also why videogame -- in
my book I use the two word, I represent it

00:13:12.250 --> 00:13:19.560
as two words "video game" whereas most of
the real serious critics and game designers

00:13:19.560 --> 00:13:25.670
I know all prefer to use the one word spelling
of it. And I now think that the one word spelling

00:13:25.670 --> 00:13:35.290
of it is a way to sorta get away from this-this-this
[Pause] the childish game like association

00:13:35.290 --> 00:13:46.339
that we have with 'em so I really regret having
spelled it with two words throughout this

00:13:46.339 --> 00:13:47.720
entire book.

00:13:47.720 --> 00:13:51.150
So egg is on [SIGHS] is on my face.

00:13:51.150 --> 00:13:56.340
I'm here to read a-a little bit of Chapter
Two. Which is a Chapter called "Head Shots".

00:13:56.340 --> 00:13:59.400
I'm going to read the first half of it. And,
it's about, about an experience I had playing

00:13:59.400 --> 00:14:01.680
games, god, about four...thirteen years ago
now. And some of you may recognize this game

00:14:01.680 --> 00:14:06.389
and some of you may not.

00:14:06.389 --> 00:14:07.389
[PAUSE]

