00:39:49.320 --> 00:39:55.270
To actually see a movie that has nothing to
do with games actually use the grammar of-of

00:39:55.270 --> 00:39:57.930
the medium in a way that feels fresh. I think
that that could be pretty cool. So I'm really

00:39:57.930 --> 00:39:58.930
looking forward to that.

00:39:58.930 --> 00:39:59.930
[PAUSE]

00:39:59.930 --> 00:40:00.930
You had a question, sir.

00:40:00.930 --> 00:40:01.930
Yes.

00:40:01.930 --> 00:40:03.130
&gt;&gt;MAN IN THE AUDIENCE: Yes, it seems like
for a game to be more than just a game a game

00:40:03.130 --> 00:40:11.580
that tells a story to be more than just a
collection of cut scenes that are stitched

00:40:11.580 --> 00:40:14.850
together? You have to give the players some
amount of control...

00:40:14.850 --> 00:40:15.850
&gt;&gt;TOM: Yeah

00:40:15.850 --> 00:40:19.840
&gt;&gt;MAN IN AUDIENCE: ...over the narrative.
Then so what do you think of the argument

00:40:19.840 --> 00:40:20.840
that if you give control over the narrative
then you can't have the same emotional impact.

00:40:20.840 --> 00:40:23.460
That you can have the tragedy then the person
can just replay it and do it in a different

00:40:23.460 --> 00:40:24.460
way. So, you can't have something like Hamlet
where the tragedy comes from the fact that

00:40:24.460 --> 00:40:31.480
there is only one way that the narrative could've
unfolded.

00:40:31.480 --> 00:40:36.940
&gt;&gt;TOM: I think that is absolutely true. Games
that are trying to be resonant in that way

00:40:36.940 --> 00:40:37.940
are doomed.

00:40:37.940 --> 00:40:44.540
But games have all sorts of other resonances.
Say you spend a lot of time in game design

00:40:44.540 --> 00:40:50.650
creating a relationship between characters,
right, that you like. The characters are well

00:40:50.650 --> 00:40:53.270
drawn, they're interesting, they're surprising,
they're not just crappy versions of action

00:40:53.270 --> 00:40:54.270
film.

00:40:54.270 --> 00:40:59.780
So say you make losing one of those characters
an irrevocable decision, or-or an irrevocable

00:40:59.780 --> 00:41:05.470
event, that if you lose this character; you
lose them. You can't go back and re-you know,

00:41:05.470 --> 00:41:10.599
you have one save slot per game and anyone
you lose along the way they're gone. You only

00:41:10.599 --> 00:41:11.599
can get them back if you start over from the
beginning of the game.

00:41:11.599 --> 00:41:16.451
That's a whole different kind of resonance
and in a moment like that where something

00:41:16.451 --> 00:41:20.290
like that happens. I-It's not going to be
Hamlet but it's not supposed to be. It-it's

00:41:20.290 --> 00:41:23.120
 -- Hamlet is a totally different kind of
aesthetic experience.

00:41:23.120 --> 00:41:30.790
But game-game play that actually assigns your
agency an awful lot of in-game meaning, that

00:41:30.790 --> 00:41:34.589
actually really doesn't screw around with
the decisions you make; that actually says

00:41:34.589 --> 00:41:38.153
you're going to make some choices, and they're
going to be difficult, and they're going to

00:41:38.153 --> 00:41:42.900
have real consequences. Not consequences you
can just kind of go back and reload.

00:41:42.900 --> 00:41:46.720
I think that is a really valuable kind of
resonance. That-that's the kind of thing that

00:41:46.720 --> 00:41:48.100
only a game can really give you.

00:41:48.100 --> 00:41:51.609
&gt;&gt;MAN IN AUDIENCE: But that makes for many,
many levels of play that being a solo person-incredibly

00:41:51.609 --> 00:41:57.079
frustrating game that a lot of people are
